    overview: "Acute promyelocytic leukemia (APL, AML-M3) is characterized by t(15;17)(q24;q21) creating the PML-RARA fusion gene. It presents with abnormal promyelocytes containing numerous Auer rods (faggot cells) and a high risk of DIC. APL is a medical emergency requiring immediate treatment with all-trans retinoic acid (ATRA). With ATRA + arsenic trioxide (ATO), APL has the best prognosis of all AML subtypes (>90% cure rate).",
    mechanismPhysiology: "t(15;17) fuses PML gene (chromosome 15) with RARA gene (retinoic acid receptor alpha, chromosome 17). PML-RARA fusion protein blocks myeloid differentiation at the promyelocyte stage. ATRA (pharmacologic doses of all-trans retinoic acid) overcomes the block → promyelocytes differentiate into mature granulocytes (differentiation therapy, not cytotoxic). Coagulopathy: abnormal promyelocytes release tissue factor and annexin II → DIC + hyperfibrinolysis → severe bleeding (leading cause of early death).",
